  "diary": "Saturday turned into exactly the kind of day I needed after a week of managing the chaos at Sea-Tac. Started slow with Jasper and coffee, then got restless and decided to hit up the farmers markets. Fremont first—spent way too long talking mushrooms with this vendor who actually grows them himself in Snoqualmie. Ended up swinging by Ballard too, grabbed a decent pastry. The whole city felt alive in that overcast way, people everywhere but not rushed.\n\nBack home, I organized everything and put on some old records I picked up last month. There's something about vinyl that makes the afternoon feel intentional. Jasper was content napping while I read. Cooked a proper dinner with the mushrooms and greens, nothing fancy but it tasted better because I knew where it came from. By evening, the house was quiet again, just me and the dog and the hum of the city outside.",
  "thought_process": "I think I was craving grounding after a stressful week. Being an air traffic controller means I'm always managing dozens of variables at once, so my days off I tend toward the opposite—slow, tactile, local. The farmers markets felt right; I wasn't trying to maximize efficiency like I do at work. I deliberately hit two markets instead of one because I wanted to linger, not optimize. The vinyl cataloging was pure comfort. I skipped the Mariners game and SoDo crowds entirely; the thought of that energy actually exhausted me. Instead, I leaned into the domestic rhythm with Jasper and cooking. The overcast weather probably helped too—it gave permission to stay inward.",
